SIMPLE: scald
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scald
<hw>Scald</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Scalded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Scalding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>eschalder</ets>, <ets>eschauder</ets>, <ets>escauder</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧chauder</ets>, fr. L. <ets>excaldare</ets>; <ets>ex + caldus</ets>, <ets>calidus</ets>, warm, hot. See <er>Ex</er>, and <er>Caldron</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To burn with hot liquid or steam; to pain or injure by contact with, or immersion in, any hot fluid; <as>as, to <ex>scald</ex> the hand</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mine own tears⟦br⟧
Do <qex>scald</qex> like molten lead.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here the blue flames of <qex>scalding</qex> brimstone fall.</q> <rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expose to a boiling or violent heat over a fire, or in hot water or other liquor; <as>as, to <ex>scald</ex> milk or meat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scald
<hw>Scald</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A burn, or injury to the skin or flesh, by some hot liquid, or by steam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scald
<hw>Scald</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[For <ets>scalled</ets>. See <er>Scall</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Affected with the scab; scabby.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Scurvy; paltry; <as>as, <ex>scald</ex> rhymers</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scald crow</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the hooded crow.</cd> <mark>[Ireland]</mark> -- <col><b>Scald head</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a name popularly given to several diseases of the scalp characterized by pustules (the dried discharge of which forms scales) and by falling out of the hair.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Scald
<hw>Scald</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Scurf on the head. See <er>Scall</er>.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scald</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Scald
<hw>Scald</hw> <pr>(sk⟦acr⟧ld <it>or</it> sk⟦add⟧ld; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>sk⟦amac⟧ld</ets>.]</ety> <def>One of the ancient Scandinavian poets and historiographers; a reciter and singer of heroic poems, eulogies, etc., among the Norsemen; more rarely, a bard of any of the ancient Teutonic tribes.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>skald</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A war song such as was of yore chanted on the field of battle by the <qex>scalds</qex> of the yet heathen Saxons.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scalder</ent>⟦br⟧
